1
00:00:41,710 --> 00:00:44,209
Blood glucose fine.
Liver function, kidney function, normal.

2
00:00:44,377 --> 00:00:46,919
Platelet count's normal.
Haemoglobin levels normal.

3
00:00:47,086 --> 00:00:49,751
Blood pressure, 131 over 92.

4
00:00:50,545 --> 00:00:52,043
Isn't this a little high?

5
00:00:52,376 --> 00:00:55,792
Weight's fine. Could do with losing
a centimetre or two off your waist.

6
00:00:55,961 --> 00:00:58,292
- Oh. Stool sample outstanding.
- Oh.

7
00:00:59,045 --> 00:01:01,586
No, that means
you haven't provided one yet.

8
00:01:01,753 --> 00:01:03,837
Yes, of course. No, I'd remember.

9
00:01:04,003 --> 00:01:06,502
You think it didn't stink or something?

10
00:01:06,670 --> 00:01:08,795
There's nothing wrong with you, Martin.

11
00:01:09,629 --> 00:01:12,254
Uh, your wife tells me
you think you're mildly depressed?

12
00:01:12,422 --> 00:01:14,421
Well, I got the sack. I'm unemployed.

13
00:01:14,588 --> 00:01:17,588
- Yes. But it wasn't your fault, was it?
- That's why I'm depressed.

14
00:01:17,755 --> 00:01:20,046
I got sacked for saying something
I didn't say.

15
00:01:20,214 --> 00:01:21,297
Try running.

16
00:01:21,465 --> 00:01:23,463
I said the opposite of what I was sacked for.

17
00:01:23,630 --> 00:01:25,380
What are you working on at the moment?

18
00:01:25,548 --> 00:01:27,423
Uh, thinking of writing a book.

19
00:01:27,589 --> 00:01:29,672
Oh! Well, that's good. What's it about?

20
00:01:29,840 --> 00:01:32,089
Russian history.

21
00:01:32,255 --> 00:01:33,631
Try running.

22
00:01:33,798 --> 00:01:37,006
The Whitehall feud between
the transport secretary Stephen Byers

23
00:01:37,133 --> 00:01:40,840
and his former press secretary
Martin Sixsmith continues to grow.

24
00:01:41,008 --> 00:01:43,757
Mr Sixsmith has been putting his side of the argument.

25
00:01:43,926 --> 00:01:46,424
Downing Street described the affair as a soap opera.

26
00:01:46,592 --> 00:01:49,592
REPORTER: There was no sign of Mr Sixsmith
at his home today,

27
00:01:49,759 --> 00:01:54,425
but after a week of trying to clear his name
in private, he's now gone public.

28
00:01:54,594 --> 00:01:58,884
He told the Sunday Times that senior figures
in government had offered him support.

29
00:01:59,052 --> 00:02:03,093
"They assured me they accepted there was
no suspicion of misconduct against me.

30
00:02:03,260 --> 00:02:06,343
I was therefore amazed
they had unilaterally 'resigned' me."

31
00:02:06,510 --> 00:02:08,135
CHOIR: ♪ Mother Of God Here I Stand

32
00:02:08,303 --> 00:02:19,178
♪ Before this icon
of your radiant brightness

33
00:02:20,679 --> 00:02:28,054
♪ Not praying to be saved...

34
00:02:28,222 --> 00:02:31,430
I would like to make a statement
regarding the circumstances

35
00:02:31,597 --> 00:02:33,888
of Mr Martin Sixsmith's resignation.

36
00:02:34,056 --> 00:02:39,263
The question here is, how long can Mr Blair
stand by his man and not himself be damaged?

37
00:02:39,431 --> 00:02:43,264
There's no doubt that there's been yet
another embarrassment for the government.

38
00:02:43,433 --> 00:02:47,431
They've not only had to eat
fantastic quantities of humble pie,

39
00:02:47,598 --> 00:02:51,139
indeed humble pie, I would say,
with a side order of grovel sauce.

40
00:02:51,975 --> 00:02:54,432
And so far as Mr Sixsmith is concerned...

41
00:03:06,434 --> 00:03:09,226
There you are.
Well, that was embarrassing.

42
00:03:09,393 --> 00:03:12,518
Father Tierney just asked me
where you disappeared to.

43
00:03:12,687 --> 00:03:17,352
Well... I don't believe in God.
And I think he can tell.

44
00:03:18,185 --> 00:03:20,059
Come on.

45
00:03:20,852 --> 00:03:23,060
- I'm worried about you, Martin.
- I did that.

46
00:03:23,228 --> 00:03:25,811
I wish you had. You need to get back to work.

47
00:03:25,978 --> 00:03:28,102
What happened to that book
on Russian history?

48
00:03:28,270 --> 00:03:30,894
No one's interested in Russian bloody history.

49
00:03:49,981 --> 00:03:52,065
(Faint voices)

50
00:03:55,022 --> 00:03:57,146
(Children squealing in background)

51
00:04:00,774 --> 00:04:02,815
(Girl giggling)

52
00:04:28,944 --> 00:04:31,902
I haven't seen you any place.
Where are you from?

53
00:04:37,151 --> 00:04:39,236
Are you from Limerick, then?

54
00:04:44,696 --> 00:04:46,737
- Hello, Philomena.
- Father.

55
00:04:46,904 --> 00:04:49,819
How have you been? How's your new hip?

56
00:04:50,654 --> 00:04:53,821
Oh, it's very good. It's titanium.

57
00:04:56,489 --> 00:04:59,905
- I haven't seen you for a while.
- I just came in to light a candle.

58
00:05:00,239 --> 00:05:02,322
Someone special?

59
00:05:03,365 --> 00:05:05,279
Yes.

60
00:05:06,156 --> 00:05:07,364
(Fairground music)

61
00:05:07,532 --> 00:05:09,655
I like your dress.

62
00:05:09,822 --> 00:05:11,239
Did you make it yourself?

63
00:05:11,406 --> 00:05:14,239
No. I bought it in a shop.

64
00:05:15,241 --> 00:05:19,907
And anyways, me auntie told me I wasn't
supposed to speak to strange men like you.

65
00:05:41,620 --> 00:05:44,284
WOMAN:
Did you let him put his hands on you?

66
00:05:44,910 --> 00:05:47,326
ANOTHER WOMAN:
Did you enjoy your sin?

67
00:05:47,827 --> 00:05:49,744
Did you take your knickers down?

68
00:05:51,495 --> 00:05:54,995
Answer Sister Hildegarde.
Did you take them down?

69
00:05:56,204 --> 00:05:57,328
Yes.

70
00:05:59,328 --> 00:06:00,995
Oh, Reverend Mother,

71
00:06:01,162 --> 00:06:03,745
at school,
the sisters never taught us about babies.

72
00:06:03,912 --> 00:06:05,370
Did your mother not tell you?

73
00:06:05,537 --> 00:06:07,622
- Her mother died ten years ago.
- Oh.

74
00:06:07,788 --> 00:06:09,371
God rest her soul.

75
00:06:13,873 --> 00:06:16,497
REVEREND MOTHER:
Don't dare blame the sisters for this.

76
00:06:16,665 --> 00:06:20,664
You are the cause of this shame.
You and your indecency.

77
00:06:20,832 --> 00:06:22,498
(Doorbell)

78
00:06:23,915 --> 00:06:25,997
(Screams and sobs)

79
00:06:29,958 --> 00:06:33,790
- (Screams)
- I don't know what to do!

80
00:06:34,791 --> 00:06:37,958
We must get a doctor.
The baby's the wrong way round. It's breech!

81
00:06:38,126 --> 00:06:41,249
It's in God's hands now.
The pain is her penance.

82
00:06:41,417 --> 00:06:46,000
Hail, holy Queen, Mother of Mercy!
Hail, holy Queen, Mother of Mercy!

83
00:06:46,167 --> 00:06:48,626
(Reverend Mother continues praying)

84
00:06:50,210 --> 00:06:52,419
Don't let her put my baby in the ground!

85
00:06:52,586 --> 00:06:55,293
It's cold in there. It's dark in there.

86
00:06:55,460 --> 00:06:57,709
(TV in background)

87
00:07:01,335 --> 00:07:04,335
Just go up and turn their lights out
in half an hour. OK?

88
00:07:04,503 --> 00:07:07,003
Doesn't she know you have a proper job?

89
00:07:07,171 --> 00:07:10,169
She's short staffed. I'm just filling in.

90
00:07:12,046 --> 00:07:14,129
I'll be home before midnight.

91
00:07:17,046 --> 00:07:19,130
Mother?

92
00:07:19,839 --> 00:07:22,504
What is it? Are you all right?

93
00:07:37,466 --> 00:07:39,381
Who is it?

94
00:07:42,966 --> 00:07:45,048
It's his birthday.

95
00:07:46,217 --> 00:07:48,299
He'll be 50 today.

96
00:07:52,799 --> 00:07:54,383
(Screams)

97
00:07:54,549 --> 00:07:55,966
Breathe.

98
00:07:59,551 --> 00:08:01,259
It's a boy.

99
00:08:01,426 --> 00:08:03,634
(Baby cries)

100
00:08:29,429 --> 00:08:31,303
Oh, Martin!

101
00:08:31,471 --> 00:08:33,053
- Hello, David.
- Hello.

102
00:08:33,640 --> 00:08:35,721
- Keith you know.
- Yes, hello again.

103
00:08:35,890 --> 00:08:40,347
And Sally Mitchell, this is Martin Sixsmith,
used to be the BBC's man in Moscow.

104
00:08:40,515 --> 00:08:41,681
- And Washington.
- Hello.

105
00:08:41,848 --> 00:08:45,430
Then he became a spin doctor for the
government, and it all went a bit tits-up.

106
00:08:45,599 --> 00:08:47,013
Is that a fair summation, Martin?

107
00:08:47,182 --> 00:08:51,015
That's fair enough. I always say,
"If you shovel shit for long enough,

108
00:08:51,181 --> 00:08:53,098
eventually you'll get some on your shoes."

109
00:08:53,266 --> 00:08:55,557
Yes, you got it on your head.
How did you manage that?

110
00:08:56,641 --> 00:08:58,140
What are you up to at the moment?

111
00:08:58,308 --> 00:09:00,849
I'm thinking of writing a book on Russian history.

112
00:09:01,018 --> 00:09:03,725
Or something else.
Maybe get back into journalism.

113
00:09:03,893 --> 00:09:06,308
I remember you!

114
00:09:06,475 --> 00:09:08,516
You're the one who sent that terrible e-mail

115
00:09:08,684 --> 00:09:11,892
saying it was a good day
to bury bad news on 9/11.

116
00:09:12,059 --> 00:09:14,432
- No, that was someone else.
- Well, I thought it was you.

117
00:09:14,602 --> 00:09:18,226
No, it's a common mistake.
On the day of Princess Margaret's funeral,

118
00:09:18,394 --> 00:09:21,351
I sent an e-mail saying
let's make sure the only thing we "bury",

119
00:09:21,519 --> 00:09:24,434
- today, is Princess Margaret.
- Which is slightly different.

120
00:09:24,602 --> 00:09:26,560
It's very different, actually... But...

121
00:09:26,728 --> 00:09:29,602
If you want to get back into journalism,
you should talk to Sally.

122
00:09:29,771 --> 00:09:34,062
I just do sob stories, human interest.
It's not really your cup of tea, is it?

123
00:09:34,229 --> 00:09:35,187
Well...

124
00:09:35,354 --> 00:09:38,644
But I'll be happy to have a look
if you want to push any ideas my way.

125
00:09:38,812 --> 00:09:40,894
Yes... Please.

126
00:09:48,272 --> 00:09:51,897
Excuse me.
Do you have a glass of Pinot Grigio?

127
00:09:53,024 --> 00:09:54,606
It's just red or white.

128
00:09:54,774 --> 00:09:57,188
I'll have white, please.

129
00:09:58,857 --> 00:10:01,231
I couldn't help overhearing you're a journalist.

130
00:10:01,399 --> 00:10:04,148
I know this woman,
she had a baby when she was a teenager

131
00:10:04,315 --> 00:10:06,731
and she's kept it secret for 50 years.

132
00:10:06,900 --> 00:10:09,023
I only found out today.

133
00:10:09,857 --> 00:10:13,191
Sorry.
The baby was taken from her by these nuns.

134
00:10:14,400 --> 00:10:17,441
- They made her have him adopted.
- Mm.

135
00:10:17,609 --> 00:10:20,441
And she's kept it a secret all this time.

136
00:10:21,152 --> 00:10:25,442
Well, the thing is, I'm working on a book
at the moment about Russian history.

137
00:10:25,609 --> 00:10:26,651
That's my thing.

138
00:10:26,819 --> 00:10:30,318
And what you're talking about would be
what they call a human interest story.

139
00:10:30,486 --> 00:10:31,986
I don't do those.

140
00:10:32,861 --> 00:10:34,442
Why not?

141
00:10:34,610 --> 00:10:39,652
Because "human interest story"
is a euphemism for stories about

142
00:10:39,819 --> 00:10:42,194
weak-minded, vulnerable, ignorant people,

143
00:10:42,362 --> 00:10:46,654
to put in newspapers read by
vulnerable, weak-minded, ignorant people.

144
00:10:47,444 --> 00:10:51,404
Not that you are.
And, yeah, anyway, I hope you find him.

145
00:10:57,946 --> 00:11:00,531
Do you think I should do a human interest story?

146
00:11:17,240 --> 00:11:19,864
Hello, you must be Philomena. I'm Martin.

147
00:11:20,032 --> 00:11:22,032
- Hello, Martin.
- Hello again.

148
00:11:22,200 --> 00:11:23,198
Hello.

149
00:11:23,367 --> 00:11:25,741
We've got a table through here. After you.

150
00:11:26,743 --> 00:11:28,824
Just to the left.

151
00:11:29,534 --> 00:11:31,700
I must apologise for the other night.

152
00:11:31,867 --> 00:11:34,074
Afraid I was a bit...
Caught me at a bad moment.

153
00:11:34,242 --> 00:11:37,241
That's all right.
I'm just glad you managed to track me down.

154
00:11:37,409 --> 00:11:39,867
I hope you don't mind coming here.
It's Mum's favourite.

155
00:11:40,035 --> 00:11:42,535
No, no, it's... it's very nice.

156
00:11:42,701 --> 00:11:44,535
Um, just...

157
00:11:49,495 --> 00:11:51,576
So, Philomena, how are you?

158
00:11:52,245 --> 00:11:53,702
I'm all right.

159
00:11:55,162 --> 00:11:57,576
I had a hip replacement last year, Martin.

160
00:11:57,745 --> 00:11:58,827
Right.

161
00:11:58,994 --> 00:12:01,161
It's much better than the bone one I had before.

162
00:12:01,328 --> 00:12:03,912
And it's titanium, so it won't rust.

163
00:12:04,079 --> 00:12:07,203
Oh. That's good, otherwise
they'd have to oil you like the Tin Man.

164
00:12:08,164 --> 00:12:09,369
Is that right?

165
00:12:09,538 --> 00:12:11,912
No, I mean, you know, like The Wizard Of Oz.

166
00:12:13,996 --> 00:12:17,622
- He's just joking, Mum.
- No, no, I'm just joking. No...

167
00:12:17,789 --> 00:12:21,455
My mother has advanced osteoarthritis
in both her knees.

168
00:12:21,623 --> 00:12:23,997
Oh. (Laughs)

169
00:12:27,416 --> 00:12:30,039
- Shall we get some salad?
- Salad, yes.

170
00:12:30,206 --> 00:12:31,289
Yes.

171
00:12:34,457 --> 00:12:38,708
Jane's the clever one in our family.
She went to university as a mature student.

172
00:12:38,875 --> 00:12:40,457
You know, when you're quite old.

173
00:12:40,625 --> 00:12:43,458
Where did you go, Martin? Oxbridge, I bet.

174
00:12:43,626 --> 00:12:46,082
You've rumbled me. Oxford, yes.

175
00:12:46,250 --> 00:12:47,624
I knew you weren't a duffer.

176
00:12:47,793 --> 00:12:51,000
- I don't think I've been in a Harvester before.
- Do they not have them in London?

177
00:12:51,168 --> 00:12:53,709
No, I tend to go to a little local place,
near where I live.

178
00:12:53,876 --> 00:12:55,751
- And where's that?
- Knightsbridge.

179
00:12:55,918 --> 00:12:58,959
Oh. Well, that must be very expensive.

180
00:13:01,128 --> 00:13:03,544
I love these little bits of toast on mine...

181
00:13:05,711 --> 00:13:07,294
And are you married, Martin?

182
00:13:07,461 --> 00:13:11,336
- Yes, I am. To Kate. 20 years.
- That's good. That's grand.

183
00:13:13,504 --> 00:13:15,586
I did love him, you know.

184
00:13:19,254 --> 00:13:22,587
I've kept what happened to me
buried away for 50 years.

185
00:13:24,129 --> 00:13:28,004
My father just left me with the nuns,
he was so ashamed.

186
00:13:28,172 --> 00:13:30,171
He told everyone I was dead.

187
00:13:30,798 --> 00:13:32,797
My family never visited me.

188
00:13:34,798 --> 00:13:39,089
After you'd had your baby,
you had to stay in the abbey for four years.

189
00:13:39,257 --> 00:13:42,923
In order to repay the sisters for taking you in,
you had to work.

190
00:13:46,174 --> 00:13:49,840
The worst jobs were in the laundry.
That's where they put me.

191
00:13:50,008 --> 00:13:53,507
I worked there seven days a week,
the whole time I was there.

192
00:13:53,676 --> 00:13:56,550
I worked there with my best friend, Kathleen.

193
00:14:08,260 --> 00:14:11,427
We were allowed to see our children
for an hour a day.

194
00:14:11,594 --> 00:14:13,676
- Come on.
- That was all.

195
00:14:16,928 --> 00:14:19,010
Walk, don't run!

196
00:14:28,595 --> 00:14:30,428
- Mary!
- Mummy.

197
00:14:48,557 --> 00:14:51,722
Anthony was best friends
with Kathleen's daughter, Mary.

198
00:14:51,890 --> 00:14:54,722
The two of them were inseparable.

199
00:14:57,598 --> 00:15:00,683
Look at that. He won't let her out of his sight.

200
00:15:03,392 --> 00:15:05,225
What's the matter?

201
00:15:05,392 --> 00:15:08,848
The girls in the kitchen said that Mother Barbara
had Mary up at the house.

202
00:15:09,017 --> 00:15:10,891
What do you think they wanted with her?

203
00:15:11,059 --> 00:15:12,516
Phil.

204
00:15:12,685 --> 00:15:14,891
I'm sure it's nothing to worry about.

205
00:15:15,059 --> 00:15:16,724
I won't be a minute.

206
00:15:19,935 --> 00:15:23,726
- Phil, I've got something for you.
- Kathleen's worried sick.

207
00:15:23,894 --> 00:15:28,019
She thinks they'll take Mary from her.
I told her they'd tell her first for sure.

208
00:15:28,187 --> 00:15:29,644
Look.

209
00:15:30,937 --> 00:15:33,019
You can't tell anyone you've got it.

210
00:15:35,478 --> 00:15:38,894
- I bet the father was handsome.
- He was. How did you get this?

211
00:15:39,062 --> 00:15:43,187
I borrowed a Box Brownie and took it
when Reverend Mother wasn't looking.

212
00:15:44,645 --> 00:15:46,395
Thank you.

213
00:15:50,104 --> 00:15:54,729
Whenever I look at that photo of Anthony,
I say a little prayer for Anunciata,

214
00:15:54,897 --> 00:15:57,396
who saved his life when I gave birth to him.

215
00:15:58,231 --> 00:16:00,397
She died a long time ago now...

216
00:16:00,565 --> 00:16:02,981
But if she hadn't taken that, I'd have nothing.

217
00:16:05,023 --> 00:16:08,565
So, were you just trapped there the whole time?

218
00:16:08,731 --> 00:16:11,523
You could only leave if you paid them £100.

219
00:16:13,774 --> 00:16:16,190
But where would I get that kind of money?

220
00:16:18,608 --> 00:16:20,692
And where would I go?

221
00:16:24,526 --> 00:16:27,108
I remember that day so clearly.

222
00:16:28,568 --> 00:16:31,316
We all knew what it meant
when a big car arrived.

223
00:16:33,027 --> 00:16:35,233
Kathleen was inconsolable.

224
00:16:35,401 --> 00:16:37,400
She knew this time they'd come for Mary.

225
00:16:37,569 --> 00:16:39,610
No, no, no, no.

226
00:17:00,447 --> 00:17:02,529
(Low conversation)

227
00:17:07,738 --> 00:17:09,821
Come away from there!

228
00:17:10,697 --> 00:17:12,656
What are you doing out here?

229
00:17:13,364 --> 00:17:15,906
I had a stomach ache, Sister Hildegarde.

230
00:17:16,614 --> 00:17:18,156
It's my time of the month.

231
00:17:18,324 --> 00:17:20,990
You're not unique in that regard.

232
00:17:21,157 --> 00:17:23,448
Put your mind to your work and it will pass.

233
00:17:32,783 --> 00:17:34,908
(Crying in background)

234
00:17:53,910 --> 00:17:56,202
Phil, it's choir practice.

235
00:18:03,787 --> 00:18:05,536
You'll be in trouble if you don't go.

236
00:18:28,290 --> 00:18:30,539
Normally, I loved to sing.

237
00:18:30,916 --> 00:18:34,082
It was one of the only things
I enjoyed in that place.

238
00:18:35,997 --> 00:18:38,998
But all I could think about was poor Kathleen.

239
00:18:41,624 --> 00:18:43,541
(Door opens and closes)

240
00:18:52,917 --> 00:18:55,583
- Philomena, they're taking Anthony.
- No, no.

241
00:18:55,750 --> 00:18:57,417
- They're taking him away.
- No.

242
00:19:02,794 --> 00:19:04,585
- Where is he?
- (Baby crying)

243
00:19:17,462 --> 00:19:19,544
(Crying)

